{
  "texts": [
    "Answering these two types of questions can be thought of as backward-looking and forward-looking counterfactual inferences (Barman & van Eck, 2021).",
    "In both cases, answering these questions involves postulating hypothetical scenarios about what would occur under a specific set of circumstances.",
    "It is this feature that we are interested in, since the ability to adequately derive these scenarios requires understanding.",
    "Similarly, there is a strong link between the quality of an explanation and the counterfactual inferences it affords (Woodward, 2003; Ylikoski & Kuorikoski, 2010; Barman, 2022).",
    "We therefore contend that the range of counterfactual infer-1 3 ences an agent can articulate is strongly related to the level of understanding (Kuorikoski & Ylikoski, 2015)."
  ]
}